  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- The USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize money laundering activities\n- Establish reporting and record-keeping requirements\n- Impose penalties for non-compliance\n\n3. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\n4. Potential Penalties:\n- Substantial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Imprisonment\n\n5. State-Level Statutes:\nMany states also have their own money laundering laws that complement federal regulations.\n\nThese statutes are designed to prevent, detect, and prosecute financial crimes involving the concealment of illegally obtained money through complex financial transactions.",
